It will be interesting to see which company turns out to be the sustainable success.

Hey Tim, I'm a proud NZer and so stoked with what Rocketlab are doing down here in Aotearoa. NZ has long been ahead of the curve when it comes to going fast, for little to no money. For example we've had Burt Munro (World's Fastest Indian), Bruce McLaren (Of McLaren F1 fame), Britten Motorcycles (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FjXA6E0eqao), Team NZ (yachting), Scott Dixon (US Indy car 5 time champ), and now ROCKETLAB. Being so far away from the rest of the world means that, in the past especially, Kiwis have had to develop a DIY attitude to building and fixing a lot of things. So proud of Rocketlab for flying the Aoteroa flag into SPACE! I hope you are enjoying your stay, Tim.

I've wondered what SpaceX could do in this market. They could go for massively oversized rocket (bad) but near complete reusability (good). Imagine an F9 first stage. Replace the interstage with a fairing which can open and close, but stays attached to the first stage. Inside the fairing is a very small second stage (perhaps similar to RocketLab's second stage) and payload. Booster stage releases second stage at altitude and does a return to launch site landing.

Compared to Rocket Lab, you're flying a much much bigger rocket but you get to reuse your booster and fairing, so you're only using up a tiny cheap second stage. $1M for the second stage, $0.5M for rocket refurbishment, $0.5M for fuel, launch pad rental, mission control staff, and you're coming in well under Rocket Lab's $5M.

My prices of course are largely guesswork, and I don't know what payload you could get to orbit like this. I imagine you need to do return-to-launch-site to get costs down enough, but I could be wrong.
The wheel wizardry was done by Gandalf.

Something to note is that although Rocket Lab is first to market, there are a good dozen or so companies spending serious money on developing rockets for this market. As a New Zealander, I hope that Rocket Lab comes out well, but it will be an interesting competition.

Incidentally, the plane window view at the end looks over our Ancestral Family Beach House near Kawakawa Bay. The little island that comes into view at about 7:42 used to be much taller, but has been quarried away to provide rich red-brown rock for gardens and footpaths all over Auckland.
